    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "@Marco Altieri: <code>replaceAll(&quot;,&quot;,&quot;.&quot;)</code> replaces all commas with dots. If there are no commas, then it does nothing. <code>Double.valueOf()</code> works (only) with strings that use dot as decimal separator. Nothing here is affected by current default locale. <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Double.html#valueOf-java.lang.String-\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/&hellip;</a>"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4304033,
      "reputation" : 3116,
      "user_id" : 3516963,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/53512fbe14f8f1e7c837175c484a69f7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "artemisian",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3516963/artemisian"
    },
    "edited" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "creation_date" : 1487006237,
    "post_id" : 4323599,
    "comment_id" : 71580681,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "The only problem with <code>replaceAll(&quot;,&quot;,&quot;.&quot;)</code> is that it&#39;ll only work if there is a single comma: ie: 1,234,567 will throw  <code>java.lang.NumberFormatException: multiple points</code>. A regex with positive lookahead will suffice <code>p.replaceAll(&quot;,(?=[0-9]+,)&quot;, &quot;&quot;).replaceAll(&quot;,&quot;, &quot;.&quot;)</code> More at: <a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/lookaround.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">regular-expressions.info/lookaround.html</a>"
  }, {
